According to the given information, the economic law that says "Bad money drives out good" is Gresham's Law. This law is named after the 16th-century English economist and financier Sir Thomas Gresham, who observed that "bad money drives out good" when the value of a currency falls. Nobel Prize winner Robert Mundell believes that Gresham's Law could be more accurately rendered, taking care of the reverse, if it were expressed as "Bad money drives out good if they exchange for the same price." The reverse of Gresham's Law, that good money drives out bad money whenever the bad money becomes nearly worthless, has been named "Thiers' law" by economist Peter Bernholz in honor of French politician and historian Adolphe Thiers.
